description.plain:
Denzel Rae Don Curry, formally known as Denzel Curry, was born in Carol City, Florida on February 16, 1995. He is of Bahamian and Native American descent.

He started rapping in 6th grade and frequently challenged others to rap battles at a local Boys & Girls club. He attended Miami’s Design And Architecture High School for his first two years of high school before being expelled. He went on to attend Carol City High School while he worked on what would become his debut album, Nostalgic 64.

Throughout 2011-2012, he posted various amateur mixtapes on SoundCloud and DatPiff such as King Remembered in 2011 and Strictly For my R.V.I.D.X.R.Z in 2012, which grabbed the attention of Earl Sweatshirt.

Not long after the group disbanded, he joined SpaceGhostPurrp’s group Raider Klan. After several disagreements between Purrp and Denzel, he would leave the group and, simultaneously, start his solo rap career, alongside the release of his SpaceGhostPurrp’s 2016 diss-track, “PURRPOSELY.”

His debut album Nostalgic 64 was released in September 2013, and was followed by a double-sided EP in June 2015 titled 32 Zel/Planet Shrooms, which included the gold-certified and breakout hit single, “ULTIMATE.”

His last release before a hiatus was his second studio album/mixtape hybrid, Imperial, which was released in March 2016.

On July 17, Denzel released his critically acclaimed third studio album, TA13OO, which was divided into three acts, released period 3 days of the complete album: “Light,” released on July 15; “Gray,” released on July 16; and “Dark,” released on July 17, alongside the entire album — After its release, it became his first charting album worldwide, peaking at #28 on the Billboard 200, and received generally positive reviews.

Almost a year after releasing the project, on May 31, 2019, Curry dropped his fourth studio album, ZUU, dedicated to his life in Carol City and inspired by the Miami culture, including features from Rick Ross, Kiddo Marv, Sam Sneak or Ice Billion Berg, the album has two supporting singles, his gold-certified single “RICKY” and “SPEEDBOAT.”

On February 7, 2020, Denzel would team up with his frequent collaborator and friend, Kenny Beats to release their collaborative 8-track project, UNLOCKED, and exactly one year later, on March 5, 2021, UNLOCKED 1.5, a re-edition of the project was released.

Nearly three years later after his latest album, on March 25, 2022, Denzel release what would be his evolution musically than he usually has with his fifth studio album, Melt My Eyez, See Your Future — The 14-track album would have 3 promotional singles during its rollout: “Walkin,” “Zatoichi” with slowthai, and “Troubles” with veteran rapper T-Pain.

description.plain:
“ULTIMATE” is the breakout hit by Florida rapper Denzel Curry. It became popular in 2016 thanks to a video meme that uses the song’s high-intensity hook to punctuate any unexpectedly “savage” moment:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1Qv2mtyLwA0

The song marks the climax of aggression on Denzel Curry’s double EP 32 Zel/Planet Shrooms. Ronny J’s chaotic production paired with Curry’s unique brand of wordplay come together for a banger that only gets more relentless as Curry’s vocals intensify in the second verse.

When asked about the song’s adoption by viral memes, Denzel said:

I made this a year ago. And to see what it did now is funny as hell, cause its like, damn, this been out, but people just now catching on to it. People feel like they’re ultimate. I feel like its a blessing that all this is happening because its bringing more attention to myself and my music.

The use of the term “ULT/Ultimate” by Denzel Curry and his C9 crew seems to have originated from this song.

description.plain:
“CLOUT COBAIN | CLOUT CO13A1N” is directed at the destructive consequences which occur as a result of chasing popularity, as heavily suggested by the title. Denzel delivers this message on one hand, through the individual dealing with suicidal thoughts and paranoia. Secondly, through the people surrounding the individual, ready to sabotage and plot against them in order to acquire their own ‘clout’.

Aesthetically, the clothes Denzel is wearing on the cover art and video are eerily similar to Kurt Cobain’s prior to his death. Also, the ‘clout’ motif is an especially interesting note on modern internet culture, when considering Denzel’s link to Kurt Cobain’s infamous sunglasses, who Denzel himself had dubbed “Clout Goggles.”

description.plain:
Built off of guttural deliveries and hard-hitting production, “SPACEGHOSTPUSSY (RIP YAMS)” is Denzel Curry’s iconic first diss track towards former friend and Raider Klan mentor SpaceGhostPurrp. The song was written in reaction to SpaceGhostPurrp’s infamous series of disrespectful tweets about A$AP Yams’s death from drug overdose on January 18, 2015. According to Curry, he originally wouldn’t want to react to the offensive comments Purrp made towards him since his departure from Raider Klan in 2013, but had to retaliate following Purrp’s comments on Yams' death.

The song features four of Curry’s “ULT House”’s then-residents, XXXTENTACION, Ski Mask the Slump God, Lofty305 and Ronny J. Denzel explained in a January 2018 interview with Montreality that the song was written after a soccer game on the first day that he actually got to know X and Ski.

Two days later, Curry and XXX released the follow-up to “SPACEGHOSTPUSSY (RIP YAMS),” “Purrposely”. SpaceGhostPurrp would retaliate on the same day with “TRAINING DAY END OF DENZEL CURRY” before Denzel proclaimed in a tweet that he had “won” and that he wouldn’t release any more diss songs towards Purrp. X released his third diss to Purrp, “#ImSippinTeainYoHood,” a month later.

description.plain:
“BLACK BALLOONS | 13LACK 13ALLOONZ” is the second track off of Denzel Curry’s third studio album, TA13OO. The track includes features from rapper GoldLink and R&B artist Twelve’Len.

Throughout the track, Denzel discusses tragic experiences and draws a variety of parallels between his own life and the movie It, as seen in the first verse of the song:

Taboo and I are in the same boat
What’s said from Pennywise, I guess we all float

In a March 2019 interview with Genius, Curry discussed the making of the song:

The original verse and the original beat … I liked the hook, but I didn’t like my verse and I didn’t like the original beat. […] I went back into the studio. It was like, ‘Hey. Yo. You should listen to the new version.’ I was like, ‘Okay. Lemme hear it.’ They played the new version, I was like, ‘Oh, alright.’

description.plain:
“RICKY” is Denzel Curry’s first single since the release of TA13OO, as well as the first single off of his fourth studio album, ZUU. The song pays tribute to and is named after Ricky, Denzel’s father—who is depicted on the cover art.

The energetic song takes the listener back to Curry’s childhood as he recalls the prescriptions of the people that influenced him, including his parents and his deceased brother Treon Johnson. The rapper reflects on the environment that influenced his early life in Carol City and on the necessity to fight back in life to achieve great things.

The song was released alongside an accompanying music video, which is inspired by the life of Denzel’s late brother Treon Johnson, who was known in Carol City to be a backyard fighter.

Denzel Curry stopped by Genius for a Verified episode and a live performance of “RICKY”.

songs.title: SUMO | ZUMO

description.plain:
First revealed at 2017’s Camp Flog Gnaw, “Sumo,” produced by G.O.O.D. Music’s Charlie Heat is the lead single off of Denzel Curry’s 2018 album, TA13OO. Curry intelligently created a lot of hype on Twitter with just the snippet of the song, as well as many performances of the song, using the Mad Man Tour with A$AP Ferg and IDK to lead us up to the official release.

The release date was delayed further due to complications with Ski Mask The Slump God’s verse “taking too long.”

The song was released on April 2nd, 2018  via Beats 1 with Zane Lowe’s “World Record,” and was exclusive to Apple Music and iTunes for a short period of time, until it was released on all platforms on April 6th, 2018.

songs.title: TABOO | TA13OO

description.plain:
The intro to his third studio album of the same title, TA13OO, shows a more soulful, melodic, and sensitive side of Denzel that hasn’t been shown before.

This song features the subject of molestation, one of the topics Denzel wanted to discuss on the project. Detailing his relationship with a young woman who grew up suffering horrible abuse, the rapper lays out the emotional distance that needs to be bridged between two damaged people. In his fractured state, Denzel offers a shoulder to cry on, a partner to pray with, and unconvincingly plays with the idea of sex as a healer. He introduces himself as ‘Denny Cascade,’ a more sensitive ego of Denzel that was first introduced on Denzel’s debut album, Nostalgic 64, and is more suitable for this track.

In a turn of events, Denzel revealed on Instagram that he too is a victim of this heinous act, having been molested as a child. This suggests that the young woman suffering abuse in the song is a metaphor for himself needing someone to rely on.

songs.title: Walkin

description.plain:
“Walkin” is the first single from Denzel Curry’s fifth studio album, Melt My Eyez, See Your Future. On the track, Denzel discusses the struggles of walking through life, dealing with the oppressive forces of capitalism and demons that come across one’s path in life.

The track’s instrumental, featuring skeletal instrumentation with female backing vocals, was teased in a more electronic form in the trailer for Melt My Eyez, See My Future.

The track was premiered on January 24, 2022 as the cover of New Music Daily with Zane Lowe on Apple Music Radio. The track’s music video, which was shot in the surroundings of the Peruvian capital city, Lima, released an hour after the song’s premiere.

songs.full_title: SWITCH IT UP | ZWITCH 1T UP by Denzel Curry
songs.title: SWITCH IT UP | ZWITCH 1T UP

description.plain:
“SWITCH IT UP | ZWITCH 1T UP” is a track where Denzel talks about fake friends and people who have betrayed him in the past. He also focuses on the topics of paranoia and bipolar disorder, which are expressed through his voice and flow.

The song was premiered July 15th, 2018, at Denzel’s concert as a part of the WOO HAH! festival in the Netherlands.

This beat’s melody is sampled from Bulgarian hip-hop artist Mom4eto’s song “Wou.”

songs.full_title: WISH by Denzel Curry (Ft. Kiddo Marv)
songs.title: WISH

description.plain:
Over production from Charlie Heat, Mickey De Grand IV and FnZ, the two Miami native rappers elaborate on their lifestyle, heavily influenced by their South Florida roots.

“WISH” serves as the third song off of ZUU, and is Denzel’s first collaboration with fellow Miami artist Kiddo Marv.

Curry names the track “Wish” because of the sample “Genie” by The B.B. & Q. Band having “your wish is my command” in the chorus.

songs.title: BLACK METAL TERRORIST | 13 M T

description.plain:
“BLACK METAL TERRORIST | 13 M T” is the last track off of Denzel Curry’s third studio album, TA13OO. It references a line from “ULT”, featured on his previous album Imperial.

Within BLACK METAL TERRORIST | 13 M T, Curry adopts his moniker of Zel, pumping himself and embracing a rap style similar to his song “Ultimate.” Curry further claims he is the greatest of all time, ‘outrapping’ his peers, as expressed in the second verse of the song:

Tortuously, killin' my infidels effortlessly
Want to impede, the P-O-P-E-D-E-A-D
Dead ‘em, I do it professionally

The song was premiered on the 15th of July, 2018 on WOO HAH! festival in the Netherlands.
